];

const faqs = [
  { q: 'Does the LG C2 42" OLED have burn-in issues?', a: 'In practice, no. LG uses a combination of pixel shifting, logo dimming, and a screen-shift feature that subtly moves the image to prevent static-element burn-in. We tested the C2 for 60 days with mixed use — movies, gaming, and a few hours of static desktop work — and saw no permanent image retention. LG has tested the panel for 100,000 hours of mixed use with no burn-in. The risk is real only if you display a static image (like a news channel ticker or PC taskbar) for 8+ hours a day, every day. If you use the C2 as a TV with varied content, burn-in is not a concern.' },
  { q: 'Can I use the LG C2 42" OLED as a PC monitor?', a: 'Yes, but with caveats. The 42-inch panel at 4K (3840x2160) has a pixel density of about 104 PPI, which is fine for media and gaming but low for text clarity at desk distance. We tested it as a monitor at a 30-inch viewing distance and found text slightly soft compared to a 32-inch 4K monitor. The 120Hz refresh and HDMI 2.1 support make it excellent for gaming, and the OLED blacks are stunning for media. The ABL (Auto Brightness Limiter) will dim the screen on bright white backgrounds, which is distracting during office work. Use it as a hybrid TV-and-gaming display, not a full-time work monitor.' },
  { q: 'How bright is the LG C2 in a bright room?', a: 'The C2 peaks at about 800 nits in HDR and 350 nits in SDR — good for a controlled-lighting room, but lower than the Samsung S95B QD-OLED (1,000+ nits) and the LG G3 (1,500 nits with MLA). In a bright room with direct sunlight, the C2 struggles — the OLED blacks remain perfect, but the highlights look washed out. We recommend the C2 for rooms with curtains or blinds, or for evening viewing. If your room gets direct sun, consider the LG G3 or a Samsung QD-OLED with higher peak brightness.' },
  { q: 'Does the LG C2 42" support 4K 120Hz gaming?', a: 'Yes. The C2 has four HDMI 2.1 ports, all supporting 4K at 120Hz, Variable Refresh Rate (VRR), Auto Low Latency Mode (ALLM), and HGiG tone mapping. We tested it with a PS5, Xbox Series X, and a PC with an RTX 4080 — all hit 4K 120Hz without issue. The input lag is 5.8ms at 120Hz and 9.2ms at 60Hz, which is among the lowest of any TV. The C2 also supports G-Sync and FreeSync for PC gaming, with VRR range from 40Hz to 120Hz.' },
  { q: 'What is the difference between the LG C2 and the LG G3?', a: 'The G3 (2023) uses a Micro Lens Array (MLA) panel that boosts peak brightness to 1,500 nits — nearly double the C2 — and it ships with a wall-mount-only design (no stand). The G3 costs about $300 more than the C2 at the same size. The C2 (2022) uses the older OLED evo panel, peaks at 800 nits, and includes a stand. For a bright room, the G3 is the better choice; for a controlled-lighting room or evening viewing, the C2 offers 90% of the picture quality at a lower price. The C2 is the better value.' },
];

const related = [
  { title: 'Best Monitor Light Bar', href: '/reviews/best-monitor-light-bar/', desc: 'Bias lighting that pairs with an OLED without washing out blacks.' },
  { title: 'Dell U2723QE Review', href: '/reviews/dell-u2723qe-review/', desc: 'A 4K USB-C monitor for desk-bound work.' },
