        brand={brand}
        rating={ratingValue}
        price={bestPrice}
        slug={productSlug}
        editorChoice={true}
      />

      <ReviewMeta
        authorSlug={authorSlug}
        lastUpdated={lastUpdated}
        testingDuration={testingDuration}
        productsTested={productsTested}
      />

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#quick-verdict">Quick Verdict</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of movies, gaming, and mixed use</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>LG C2 42&Prime; OLED</strong> is the best small-screen OLED you can buy in 2026. The perfect blacks, infinite contrast, and 120Hz 4K gaming make it stunning for movies and PS5 or Xbox use. At $999 it is expensive for a 42-inch panel, and the peak brightness trails the LG G3 — but if you watch in a controlled-lighting room, the C2 delivers 90% of the picture quality of the G3 at a lower price.
      </div>

      <p>LG launched the C2 in 2022 as the successor to the C1, and it remains the smallest true OLED TV on the market at 42 inches. The C2 uses LG's OLED evo panel — a brighter, more efficient variant of standard OLED — with the a9 Gen 5 processor for upscaling and AI picture tuning. We bought the C2 at retail and put it through 60 days of movies, gaming, and occasional desktop use to see whether a $999 42-inch OLED is worth it over a similarly priced LCD or a larger 48-inch OLED.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against the LG G3 and Samsung QD-OLED alternatives, see our <a href="/reviews/dell-u2723qe-review/">Dell U2723QE review</a> for a desktop-monitor alternative. If you want bias lighting that pairs with an OLED without washing out the blacks, the <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-light-bar/">best monitor light bar</a> roundup covers our picks.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Picture Quality: Perfect Blacks and Infinite Contrast</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of the C2 is its OLED panel. Unlike LCD TVs that use a backlight and selectively block light through liquid crystals, OLED pixels are self-emissive — each pixel produces its own light and turns off completely to display black. The result is a true zero-light black level and an effectively infinite contrast ratio. In a dark room, the C2 produces star fields and space scenes where the black areas emit no light at all, which is impossible on any LCD.</p>

      <p>In our testing, the C2 delivered the best picture quality we have seen in a sub-$1,000 TV. Dolby Vision content on Netflix and Apple TV showed specular highlights — explosions, lamp filaments, sunlight on water — with a punch that no LCD can match, while the shadows retained detail that LCDs crush. The a9 Gen 5 processor upscales 1080p content well, though 480p and 720p sources show their age. The C2 handles 24p cinema correctly with no judder, and motion interpolation (LG's TruMotion) is smooth without the soap-opera effect if you set it to User and minimize the sliders.</p>

      <p>The OLED evo panel is brighter than the standard OLED in the C1 — about 20% brighter in our measurements, peaking at 800 nits in HDR. This is good, but it trails the Samsung S95B QD-OLED (1,000+ nits) and the LG G3 with MLA (1,500 nits). In a dark room, the difference is invisible; in a bright room, the brighter panels hold their highlights better against ambient light.</p>

      <h3>Gaming: 4K at 120Hz with HDMI 2.1</h3>
      <p>The C2 is one of the best gaming TVs you can buy. All four HDMI ports are HDMI 2.1, supporting 4K at 120Hz, Variable Refresh Rate (VRR), Auto Low Latency Mode (ALLM), and HGiG tone mapping. We tested it with a PS5, an Xbox Series X, and a PC with an RTX 4080 — all hit 4K 120Hz without issue, and the input lag measured 5.8ms at 120Hz and 9.2ms at 60Hz, which is among the lowest of any TV.</p>

      <p>The C2 supports both G-Sync and FreeSync for PC gaming, with a VRR range from 40Hz to 120Hz. We tested it with Cyberpunk 2077 at 4K with HDR and ray tracing on, and the C2 rendered neon reflections and streetlights with a depth that no LCD can match. The OLED response time is 0.1ms — effectively instant — so there is no ghosting or motion blur in fast-paced games. This is the single biggest advantage of OLED over LCD for gaming.</p>

      <p>The Game Optimizer menu groups all gaming settings — VRR, ALLM, HDR tone mapping, motion settings — into a single quick-access bar. It is well-designed and saves digging through the full settings menu. The C2 also supports Dolby Vision Gaming at 4K 120Hz, which the Xbox Series X uses for titles like Forza Horizon 5 — the highlights are noticeably punchier than standard HDR10.</p>

      <h3>Brightness and ABL: The Trade-Offs of OLED</h3>
      <p>The C2's peak brightness of 800 nits in HDR is good for a controlled-lighting room but lower than competing QD-OLEDs and the LG G3. In a bright room with direct sunlight, the C2 struggles — the OLED blacks remain perfect, but the highlights look washed out and the overall image is dim. If your room gets direct sun, consider the LG G3 or a Samsung S95B QD-OLED with higher peak brightness, or plan to use curtains during daytime viewing.</p>

      <p>The ABL (Auto Brightness Limiter) is the more noticeable trade-off. ABL dims the entire screen when a high percentage of pixels are bright (a white web page, a snowy scene, a bright sports stadium) to protect the OLED panel from overcurrent. In practice, this means a sudden dim when you switch from a dark movie to a bright web page, or when a sports broadcast cuts to a wide stadium shot. It is not severe, but it is visible, and it is the most common complaint from new OLED owners. You can reduce the effect by lowering the OLED Pixel Brightness to 80-90, but you cannot disable ABL entirely.</p>

      <p>For SDR content, the C2 peaks at about 350 nits — enough for most rooms, but lower than mid-range LCDs that hit 500+ nits. In a bright office or a sunlit living room, the C2 will look dim for daytime TV. In an evening viewing room or a home theater, the C2 is stunning.</p>

      <h3>Smart Platform and Audio: WebOS Is Fast but Ad-Supported</h3>
      <p>The C2 runs LG's WebOS smart platform on the a9 Gen 5 processor. WebOS is fast — apps launch in 2 to 3 seconds, navigation is smooth, and the home screen loads instantly. All major streaming apps are present: Netflix, Disney+, Apple TV, YouTube, Amazon Prime Video, Hulu, and HBO Max. The app selection is on par with Roku and Apple TV, and the built-in tuner supports over-the-air channels via an antenna.</p>

      <p>The catch is that the WebOS home screen is ad-supported. Sponsored content appears as a row on the home screen, and LG promotes its own services (LG Channels) prominently. You cannot disable these ads entirely, though you can rearrange the home screen to push them down. If you want an ad-free smart TV experience, use an Apple TV 4K or a Roku Streaming Stick instead of the built-in WebOS.</p>

      <p>Audio is the C2's weak point. The 2.2-channel speakers (20W total) are clear but thin — there is no bass, and dialogue can sound boxed in during loud scenes. The C2 supports Dolby Atmos but only decodes it; it cannot produce a real Atmos experience from two speakers. We recommend pairing the C2 with a soundbar — the Sony HT-G700 or the Sonos Beam (Gen 2) are good matches at $400 to $500. Note that the C2 does not decode DTS-HD or DTS:X audio, so if you have a DTS Blu-ray collection, you will need a receiver that decodes DTS.</p>

      <h3>Design and Inputs: Thin, Elegant, and Well-Connected</h3>
      <p>The C2 is one of the best-designed TVs you can buy. The bezel is 0.25 inches thin on three sides — nearly flush with the image — and the panel is 1.8 inches deep at its thickest point, with a flush wall-mount profile for a clean look. The stand is a center-mounted aluminum base that is stable and raises the panel about 2 inches off the surface, leaving room for a soundbar underneath. The build quality is excellent for the price.</p>

      <p>All four HDMI ports are HDMI 2.1, supporting the full 48Gbps bandwidth for 4K 120Hz. There is also a single USB 2.0 port (for media playback, not power), an Ethernet port, an optical audio out, a 3.5mm headphone jack, and an antenna input. The lack of USB-C is a minor annoyance — you cannot power a streaming stick from the TV's USB port while using HDMI, because the USB port is underpowered.</p>

      <p>The Magic Remote is excellent — it works like a Wii remote, with point-and-click navigation and a scroll wheel. Voice search works well for launching apps and finding content. The remote has a backlight that activates in low light, which is a nice touch. The remote is the same across all LG 2022 and 2023 TVs, so if you have owned an LG before, you will be immediately familiar.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>The C2 competes against the LG G3, the Samsung S95B QD-OLED, and the Sony A80K. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>TV</th>
            <th>Price (42-48")</th>
            <th>Panel</th>
            <th>Peak Brightness</th>
            <th>HDMI 2.1</th>
            <th>Stand</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
