      <p>The <strong>LG G3</strong> (2023) uses a Micro Lens Array (MLA) panel that nearly doubles the peak brightness to 1,500 nits, and it ships wall-mount-only with no stand. It costs about $300 more than the C2 at the same size. For a bright room, the G3 is the clear winner; for a controlled-lighting room or evening viewing, the C2 offers 90% of the picture quality at a lower price. The G3 is the better TV, but the C2 is the better value.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Samsung S95B QD-OLED</strong> (2022) uses a Samsung Display QD-OLED panel that hits 1,000+ nits with better color volume than LG's W-OLED. It supports HDR10+ (not Dolby Vision) and has Tizen (not WebOS) as its smart platform. The S95B is brighter and more colorful, but it does not support Dolby Vision, which is a dealbreaker for some. The smallest QD-OLED is 55 inches — there is no 42-inch option.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Sony A80K</strong> (2022) uses the same LG Display OLED panel as the C2 but with Sony's XR processing, which is generally considered the best in the industry for motion and upscaling. The A80K costs $200 more than the C2, has only two HDMI 2.1 ports (vs four on the C2), and peaks at 700 nits. If you value motion processing and Sony's color science, the A80K is the pick — but the C2 offers more HDMI 2.1 ports and a lower price.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the C2 if you want the best small-screen OLED and you watch in a controlled-lighting room. The perfect blacks, infinite contrast, and 120Hz 4K gaming make it stunning for movies and next-gen consoles. At $999, it is the only 42-inch true OLED on the market.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. The C2 drops to $799 around Black Friday and Prime Day, and we have seen it as low as $749 during clearance events. The C2 is being replaced by the C3 (2023) and C4 (2024), so clearance pricing on the C2 will continue through 2026. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the C2 and buy the LG G3 if your room is bright. The G3's MLA panel hits 1,500 nits — nearly double the C2 — and holds its highlights against direct sunlight. The G3 costs $300 more and is wall-mount-only, but for a bright living room, the brightness is worth it.</p>

      <p>Consider the Samsung S95B QD-OLED if you want higher brightness and color volume and do not need Dolby Vision. The S95B hits 1,000+ nits with a wider color gamut, but it supports HDR10+ instead of Dolby Vision, and the smallest size is 55 inches. If you have the space for a 55-inch panel, the S95B is a strong alternative.</p>

      <p>Buy a soundbar. The C2's built-in speakers are thin and lack bass, and they cannot produce real Dolby Atmos. A $400 soundbar like the Sony HT-G700 or the Sonos Beam (Gen 2) transforms the experience. Pair the C2 with a <a href="/reviews/best-monitor-light-bar/">monitor light bar</a> for bias lighting that reduces eye strain without washing out the OLED blacks.</p>

